{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518584"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:06:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:06:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12937"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12937"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.23,0.59,0.04,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5375"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52624"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5375"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12937"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37986"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1175"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9801"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9935"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15341"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52624"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a one-week history of easy bruising, fatigue, and confusion. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 145/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. She is pale and lethargic with scattered petechiae and ecchymoses on her arms and legs. Neurological examination reveals mild disorientation and confusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 110 g/L (125-160)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelet count: 120 x10\u003Csup\u003E9/\u003C/sup\u003EL (150-450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELDH: 320 U/L (105-230)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPeripheral blood smear: Schistocytes present\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum creatinine: 180 \u03bcmol/L (50-120)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EADAMTS13 activity: \u0026lt;10% (\u0026gt;50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Immune thrombocytopenic purpura","Haemolytic uraemic syndrome","Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura","Disseminated intravascular coagulation","Von Willebrand disease"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Ethrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura (TTP)\u003C/strong\u003E. TTP is a rare but potentially fatal blood disorder characterised by thrombocytopenia, microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, and varying degrees of organ damage. The classic pentad of TTP includes thrombocytopenia, microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, neurological symptoms, renal impairment, and fever, although not all features need to be present for diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the patient presents with thrombocytopenia (120 x 10^9/L), evidence of haemolysis (elevated LDH, presence of schistocytes), neurological symptoms (confusion), and renal impairment (elevated creatinine). The ADAMTS13 activity of \u0026lt;10% is diagnostic of TTP, as it indicates a severe deficiency of this von Willebrand factor-cleaving enzyme.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmune thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP)\u003C/strong\u003E is an autoimmune disorder characterised by isolated thrombocytopenia. While it can cause easy bruising, it does not typically cause the microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia (evidenced by schistocytes) or organ dysfunction seen in this patient. Additionally, ADAMTS13 deficiency is not a feature of ITP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemolytic uraemic syndrome (HUS)\u003C/strong\u003E can present similarly to TTP with microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, thrombocytopenia, and acute kidney injury. However, HUS is typically associated with a preceding diarrhoeal illness (often due to E. coli infection) and does not usually cause the severe ADAMTS13 deficiency seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC)\u003C/strong\u003E can also cause thrombocytopenia and microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia. However, DIC is usually secondary to another condition such as sepsis, trauma, or malignancy, which are not evident in this case. DIC would also typically show abnormalities in coagulation studies, which are not mentioned here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVon Willebrand disease\u003C/strong\u003E is a bleeding disorder caused by deficiency or dysfunction of von Willebrand factor. While it can cause easy bruising, it does not cause the microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia or organ dysfunction seen in this patient. Von Willebrand disease is also typically a congenital condition, unlike the acute presentation in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of TTP is supported by the clinical presentation, laboratory findings (especially the presence of schistocytes and severe ADAMTS13 deficiency), and the absence of other explanatory conditions. Prompt recognition and treatment of TTP is crucial, as it can be life-threatening if left untreated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura (TTP) typically presents with thrombocytopenia, microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, renal impairment, and neurological symptoms.","TTP is caused by a deficiency of ADAMTS13, a von Willebrand factor-cleaving enzyme, which can be acquired or congenital.","The presence of schistocytes on peripheral blood smear is a key diagnostic feature of TTP."],"references":["Sukumar S, L\u00e4mmle B, Cataland SR. Thrombotic Thrombocytopenic Purpura: Pathophysiology, Diagnosis, and Management. J Clin Med. 2021 Feb 2;10(3):536. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7867179/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37986"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12937"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37986"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-07T21:10:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-07T21:11:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5375"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52624"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7